    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Music for Nothing</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Chris P Schachter letter, commenting on June 29 column, suggests putting bandwidth restrictions on Napster file-sharing</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Perhaps I'm a dull-witted consumer, but how does Napster's distribution of music (''Napster Rocks the Web,'' State of the Art, June 29) differ from the ''used/cut out/promotional copy -- not for sale'' section in every mom-and-pop record store in the country? Should we close the site and send out an army of copyright cops to slam the door on thousands of small businesses? If anything, we should just mandate bandwidth restrictions (56k?) on Napster file-sharing, so the site becomes a huge ''sample and buy'' boon to the ''dying'' recorded music industry.</p>
        <p>CHRIS P. SCHACHTER  New York City</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Perhaps I'm a dull-witted consumer, but how does Napster's distribution of music (''Napster Rocks the Web,'' State of the Art, June 29) differ from the ''used/cut out/promotional copy -- not for sale'' section in every mom-and-pop record store in the country? Should we close the site and send out an army of copyright cops to slam the door on thousands of small businesses? If anything, we should just mandate bandwidth restrictions (56k?) on Napster file-sharing, so the site becomes a huge ''sample and buy'' boon to the ''dying'' recorded music industry.</p>
        <p>CHRIS P. SCHACHTER  New York City</p>
